{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506096"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2517"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2517"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.36,0.06,0.2,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50254"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2517"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35518"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"404"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14057"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14070"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50254"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of right hip pain after a fall at home. She was unable to get up from the floor and her husband called an ambulance. She has a medical history of early Alzheimer\u0027s dementia and osteoporosis. Her regular medications are alendronate and calcium supplements. She does not smoke and lives at home with her husband.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in discomfort with vital signs within normal limits. She is unable to ambulate and there is limited movement of the right hip due to pain. The right leg appears shortened and externally rotated. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Total hip arthroplasty","Hemiarthroplasty","Conservative management with bed rest","Internal fixation","Palliation and comfort care"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a typical history and examination findings of a hip fracture. The X-ray shows a valgus impacted subcapital fracture, which is classified as a Garden type I fracture. The choice of management for hip fractures depends on several factors, including the type and degree of fracture displacement (Garden classification), patient age, and comorbidities. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor Garden type I and II fractures (undisplaced or minimally displaced), \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal fixation, \u003C/strong\u003Etypically using cannulated hip screws or a dynamic hip screw, is generally recommended regardless of age, as it preserves the native hip joint and has a lower risk of complications compared to arthroplasty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal hip arthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehemiarthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E are typically reserved for displaced fractures (Garden type III and IV) in older patients (usually over 65 years). The choice between these two options depends on factors such as pre-fracture mobility and cognitive function. In this case, the undisplaced nature of the fracture makes arthroplasty less appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management\u003C/strong\u003E with bed rest is generally not recommended for hip fractures in elderly patients who are medically fit for surgery, as it is associated with higher mortality rates and poorer functional outcomes. Surgical management allows for earlier mobilization and reduces complications associated with prolonged immobility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPalliation and comfort care\u003C/strong\u003E would only be considered in patients with very limited life expectancy or those who are too frail to undergo any surgical intervention. This patient, while having some comorbidities, does not appear to fall into this category based on the information provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, internal fixation is the most appropriate management for this patient\u0027s Garden type I fracture, as it offers the best balance of preserving hip function while minimizing surgical risk in the context of her age and comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Garden type 1 fractures are ideally treated by internal fixation.","The choice between internal fixation and arthroplasty for hip fractures depends on the degree of displacement (Garden stage) and patient factors.","Surgical management is preferred over conservative management for most hip fractures in the elderly, if the patient is medically fit for surgery."],"references":["Bhandari M, Swiontkowski M. Management of Acute Hip Fracture. N Engl J Med. 2017;377:2053-62. Available at a: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1611090","Callaghan JJ, Haidukewych GJ. Subcapital fractures: a changing paradigm. J Bone Joint Surgical Br. 2012;94:19-21. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23118374/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35518"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2517"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17164"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17